A RESOLUTION
1 Honoring the legacy of the 6888th Central Postal Directory Battalion; and for other purposes.
2 WHEREAS, the 6888th Central Postal Directory Battalion, nicknamed the "Six Triple
3 Eight," was an all-Black battalion of the United States Women's Army Corps that managed
4 postal services from 1945 to 1946; and
5 WHEREAS, there was a significant shortage of soldiers who were able to manage the postal
6 service for the United States Army overseas during World War II, resulting in millions of
7 pieces of undelivered mail; and
8 WHEREAS, led by Major Charity Adams, the battalion consisted of 855 women and was the
9 only predominantly Black United States Women's Army Corps unit sent overseas during
10 World War II; and
11 WHEREAS, while most of the women of the 6888th served as postal clerks, some served as
12 cooks, mechanics, and other support positions, enabling the Six Triple Eight to operate as a
13 self-sufficient unit; and
